  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Refining Selection Accuracy**\n\nI\'m zeroing in on the selection logic. It\'s frustratingly \"jumping\" around instead of precisely selecting what\'s under the cursor or finger. I want to ensure it only highlights what\'s directly touched, no assumptions allowed! I\'m focusing on edge cases, to be sure I can create an accurate, predictable tool.\n\n\n**Analyzing Selection Behavior**\n\nI\'m now investigating how `pointer-events: none` on the text layer affects selection drags. I suspect this might cause the selection to \"snap\" or stop updating when the finger moves from a text element to empty space. The user wants precise word selection, and I want to fix those edge cases. I\'ll test how different pointer events effect how selections are handled.\n\n\n**Addressing Selection Inconsistencies**\n\nI\'m wrestling with browser selection quirks in the text layer, which is causing inaccurate selections. The \"smart\" word and line-snapping are a problem. The PDF text layer layout, with overlapping spans, is exacerbating things and causing those line-snapping issues. I\'ll need to minimize these hit-area inconsistencies and, if possible, prevent smart selection. I\'m considering re-enabling `pointer-events`, but making the spans tighter to mitigate unwanted expansions. Our logic maps browser selections; so, I have to ensure the browser selection is precise and reliable.\n\n\n**Investigating Span Interactions**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the behavior of `pointer-events` in relation to span interaction within the PDF text layer, I\'m thinking about how the spans\' `pointer-events: auto` might be affected by the container\'s `pointer-events: none`, especially in relation to the behavior of selection. Specifically, I\'m considering the potential impact of \"gaps\" between spans on selection start and drag behavior. I am also recalling that the current logic will map the browser selection. My focus is on ensuring those browser selections are precise and reliable. I need to make sure I understand how to deal with the existing PDF approach.\n\n\n**Refining Selection Adhesion**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how horizontal drags \"fall off\" line spans, causing browser selection jumps. I\'m thinking of ways to prevent this. I may consider maintaining `pointer-events: auto` on the `textLayer` while making spans `inline` with no padding, and then, using `rawRects`. Finally, I want to add some horizontal stickiness to avoid the line-jumping, but ensuring it is very thin vertically to avoid overlap. It is likely that the current container logic is sufficient to prevent the \"first word\" problem.\n\n\n**Examining Container Interactions**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential causes for unexpected selections. I\'ve re-examined the code and confirmed the text layer has `pointer-events: none`, but suspect the browser might still initiate selection if *any* text is selectable in the container. I am thinking of methods to stop the browser from \"guessing\". However, a quick scan of the CSS suggests disabling multi-line selection entirely at the CSS level would not work.\n\n\n**Adjusting Span Robustness**\n\nI\'m now thinking about how to create robust hit areas for selection without compromising character-level accuracy. I\'m focusing on making the spans taller, *but* keeping them aligned perfectly to the baseline, which should allow for a more resilient selection area while using `rawRects` for precise highlighting. This addresses the browser\'s \"guessing\" behavior and ensures selection remains accurate to the character, even with less-than-perfect finger precision. My goal is to prevent jumps to other lines and ensure the spans are the only selection handles, while still offering consistent behavior when the user drags the mouse, or uses a finger.\n\n\n**Revising Container Behavior**\n\nI\'m now changing the `textLayer`\'s `pointer-events` from `none` to `auto`, as the previous setting seems to be causing the selection to \"jump\" or select the first word. I\'m hoping this will make the browser treat the container as an accessible selection target. I will also make the spans vertically taller to stabilize the line selections. My focus is on ensuring the container provides a proper hit area for selections, even if it is not a span.\n\n\n**Improving Line Selections**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on accurate line selections. The aim is to prevent the browser\'s \"end of line\" behavior from selecting unintended lines. I\'m focusing on making lines end in the container. To fix \"select lines I didn\'t touch\", I\'ll use inline-block display and vertical-align to fix that issue, and vertical expansion to capture finger drags.\n\n\n**Analyzing Selection Initiation**\n\nI\'m now investigating selection initiation, specifically how clicking in empty space within the container triggers unwanted word selection. The browser\'s `user-select: text` is the culprit. When clicking empty space within the container, the browser starts a selection from the first \"logical\" position it can find. This confirms that I need to ensure the spans are properly positioned. It\'s time to create accurate representations of the text for the browser. I\'ll focus on how the spans represent text, and how disjoint spans affect selection range.\n\n\n**Implementing User Selection**\n\nI\'m now implementing `user-select: none` on the text layer container and `user-select: text` on the spans, along with restoring `pointer-events: auto`. My goal is to force selection to start on characters and to constrain selections to spans. I\'m focusing on the interaction between container and span `user-select` properties to ensure precise selection behavior. I\'ll need to check the exact behavior when the user drags between spans.\n\n\n**Evaluating Selection Accuracy**\n\nI\'m now evaluating the accuracy of the selection after considering various approaches. I\'m focusing on the current range to understand *exactly* what the browser highlights based on user input. I\'ve realized that the browser includes words that aren\'t *directly* under the finger when generating a range. While I can\'t easily change the browser\'s selection engine, I\'m considering using `caretPositionFromPoint` to manually set the selection, though this is essentially re-implementing selection logic. I\'ll start with a CSS-focused approach, with `user-select` isolation.\n\n\n**Isolating Selection Sources**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how to prevent the browser from initiating selections from the document or body, when clicks fall through. The `pointer-events: none` on the container *should* prevent this, but I\'ll double-check the z-index to make sure the text layer fully covers the content, and no clicks are allowed to bubble. My goal is to completely isolate browser selection to the span elements. The current code prevents initial, unintentional selections, but I need to make sure this is never a possible scenario.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 25
      nanos: 644330951
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
