  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Addressing a Browser Anomaly**\n\nI\'ve been wrestling with a subtle quirk: `getClientRects()` occasionally returns these \"magic\" rectangles that are broader than the actual text due to browser selection logic, like spaces. This poses a challenge. Currently, the main focus.\n\n\n**Refining User Selection**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on a safer approach for user selection within the text layer. I realized directly disabling `user-select` on the container can be problematic, particularly in Safari. Instead, I\'m leaning toward keeping the container\'s `user-select: text` and using a `:empty` element or background element with `pointer-events: none` to prevent unintended interactions. This ensures that clicks on the background don\'t interfere with text selection on child spans, and will improve interactions.\n\n\n**Implementing User Selection**\n\nI\'m now implementing the `select-none` on the page div, as the user wants to start selection on the selected word only. With this combination, clicking empty space will not start a selection, and clicking on a text span will start the selection. This aligns with the preferred user interaction.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 6
      nanos: 558354825
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
