  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Implementing Character Selection**\n\nI\'ve recently disabled background page selection, and `.textLayer` container selection. Now, only characters can be selected. I achieved this with `select-none` on the container, and `user-select: none;` on the `.textLayer`. Next I need to figure out how to best handle a drag event.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I have updated the selection logic to be extremely precise, following your request to only select what is directly under your finger/mouse without any \"guessing.\"\n\n**Key changes implemented:**\n1.  **Strict Hit Zones:** Selection can now **only** start if you touch a character directly. Clicks on empty space between words or lines are now explicitly ignored by the selection engine.\n2.  **No More \"Guessing\":** I removed all logic that tried to \"predict\" or merge rectangles. The highlight now follows the browser\'s most literal report of what is selected (`rawRects`).\n3.  **Background Lockdown:** The page background is now set to `user-select: none`. This prevents the browser from \"snapping\" selection to the start of a paragraph or jumping across lines when you drag your finger into empty space.\n4.  **Character Isolation:** Each text span is now its own isolated handle. By disabling selection on the container and only enabling it on the text, the browser\'s \"smart selection\" (which often causes unwanted multi-line jumps) is suppressed.\n\nThis creates a \"What You Touch Is What You Get\" experience. If you find it\'s too difficult to select multiple words due to this strictness, please let me know, and we can add back a *tiny* (pixel-thin) bridge between characters."
    thinking_duration {
      nanos: 148689506
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
