  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Addressing the Jumps**\n\nI\'m currently wrestling with this irritating \"jumping\" text selection issue in the PDF reader. I\'ve been experimenting with ways to prevent the selection from expanding to the whole page when my cursor reaches the end of a line or drifts into whitespace, but so far no luck. My focus is on the boundary conditions.\n\n\n**Refining the Boundaries**\n\nI\'m now implementing `pointer-events: none` on the text layer and `pointer-events: auto` on the spans within. I\'ve also added `select-none` to the parent container. The `handleSelection` function iterates through spans for `selectionRects`. I believe the browser\'s selection engine may be causing the issue if it\'s struggling to determine a bounded selection. The `rawRects` calculation also warrants a closer look. I need to figure out why dragging into the \"dead space\" is making the selection expand.\n\n\n**Investigating the Root Cause**\n\nI\'ve made a crucial discovery: I inadvertently removed key CSS related to \"dead space\" handling. The core problem, I now understand, is the tendency for the selection to jump and expand to the entire page, especially on iOS/Safari and certain Chrome versions, when it\'s dragged outside the initial element\'s bounds. The issue is likely the browser\'s difficulty determining the \"next\" selectable element. My focus is now on how `window.getSelection()` calculates `rawRects`.\n\n\n**Verifying the CSS**\n\nOkay, I\'ve got a handle on how the browser\'s `Selection` object behaves when dragging into whitespace. I see now that if the selection handle hits \"dead space\", the selection can jump to the entire textLayer if the textLayer container itself is selectable. I believe the culprit is likely to be improper CSS rules. I\'m focusing my attention now on the `src/index.css` file, specifically the `textLayer` class, to verify that `pointer-events: none` is correctly implemented, so that my text layer should not be selectable.\n\n\n**Analyzing the Span Logic**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on a potential flaw in the `handleSelection` function and the way the browser\'s selection range interacts with the spans. I suspect the core issue might stem from the way the selection expands to encompass the whole text layer, especially if it includes multiple lines or the parent container. The `selection.containsNode(span, true)` check is now my prime focus. I\'m re-evaluating the span handling logic.\n\n\n**Constraining the Range**\n\nI\'m now investigating what happens when a user drags a selection far away from the initial selection, which makes the browser expand the selection range. My goal is to ensure the selection encompasses only the characters the finger actually touches, rather than expand it unnecessarily. I\'m focusing on the `rawRects` generation in `PDFReader.tsx`, specifically how the selection logic interacts with spans, and addressing the whole-page jump issue.\n\n\n**Refining the Logic**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the interaction between `selection.containsNode(span, true)` and the browser\'s native selection behavior. My gut feeling is that it is too permissive. Now I\'m considering using `caretRangeFromPoint` or `elementFromPoint` in a custom `onTouchMove` to provide improved precision to the selection rects and prevent the parent container from becoming a selection target. Also, I\'m checking for Apple devices and Safari, because these browsers have different behaviors. Furthermore, my goal is now matching the user\'s explicit intent of selecting the character under their finger.\n\n\n**Implementing a Selection Guard**\n\nI\'m now considering a custom selection handler to improve precision and avoid the browser\'s \"helpful\" but often undesirable text selection behavior. The jump to whole page issue is likely related to absolutely positioned spans and the browser\'s DOM traversal logic between lines. I\'ll experiment with a \"Selection Clamp\" and review the display properties, especially padding on `textLayer span`.\n\n\n**Re-evaluating Selection Method**\n\nI\'m revisiting the use of manual span iteration. While it offers fine-grained control, I now recognize `range.getClientRects()` provides more accurate selection boundaries, crucial for preventing the jump to whole-page selection. I suspect transformed or scaled elements might cause issues, but accuracy is paramount here. I\'m going to test the results now, to see if it works.\n\n\n**Simplifying the Selection**\n\nI\'m now optimizing the selection loop, aiming for elegance and precision. I\'m swapping the span iteration with `range.getClientRects()`. My thinking is that this method should give me better accuracy in the selection boundaries, even with potential element transformations, and this might be the key to fixing the jump. I need to see if it fixes the issue.\n\n\n**Eliminating the Jump**\n\nI\'ve just had a breakthrough. Using `range.getClientRects()` has proven more accurate than iterating spans, but the whole-page jump persists. I realized that my previous efforts might have been hampered by the container being selectable. Now I\'m meticulously checking the `PDFReader.tsx` file for any unexpected programmatic selection or the container\'s selection capabilities. My focus is now on rigorously preventing the container from becoming a selection target.\n\n\n**Preventing the Selection Jump**\n\nI\'ve just confirmed my suspicion about the container\'s selectability. Though CSS and code explicitly prevent selection on the textLayer, the browser\'s behavior is still odd. I\'m rigorously checking the `PDFReader.tsx` code for anything that might inadvertently allow container selection, like the root being a selectable element. I need to make the container itself impossible to select to fix the jump.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 20
      nanos: 699847682
    }
