  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Potential Issues**\n\nI\'ve examined the code and the `Selection` object appears problematic. It could be returning unintended `Range` objects, particularly on mobile where user selections might unintentionally span multiple document sections. I\'m focusing on scenarios where dragging can expand the selection beyond the intended scope, and how to prevent it.\n\n\n**Refining Selection Boundaries**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the interaction between the PDF.js text layer and browser selection behavior. The `pdfjs.renderTextLayer` creates a unique internal structure within `textLayerDivRef.current`, and I need to ensure that only the contents of this div are selectable. I\'ve realized the browser\'s \"helpfulness\" is a factor, potentially causing selections to prematurely end. Additionally, I\'m reconsidering the implications of `user-select: none` on the container element and its children in `index.css`.\n\n\n**Isolating the Selection**\n\nI\'m now focusing on enforcing boundaries for user selections within the text layer. My recent investigation revealed that even if a user attempts a selection outside the intended text layer, the browser might unexpectedly expand the selection. Now, I\'m using `range.getClientRects()` to verify the selection area, and ensuring the selection remains constrained within my text layer\'s boundaries. I\'ll test to see if I can force the selection to remain inside the text layer, regardless of mouse drags.\n\n\n**Investigating Mouse Events**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential interactions between `pointer-events: none` on the container and the selection engine. The current approach involves checking the `mousedown`/`touchstart` event. I plan to use `Selection.setBaseAndExtent` to clamp selection if it leaves the layer, but that\'s complex, and I\'m reconsidering it. Revisiting the `:after` gaps that I previously tried to \"fill in the gaps\" might be useful. The user said it was better previously.\n\n\n**Reconsidering Select Control**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how the browser interprets selections that reach the end of a sentence within the text layer. If a user selects text and drags to the end, it\'s jumping to select the entire page, and this indicates a failure of the selection boundary logic. I\'m exploring an approach using the text layer as a transparent selection target with `user-select: text` on the container, to see if it provides better control.\n\n\n**Revisiting Gap Fillers**\n\nI\'m now reconsidering filling the gaps between spans with invisible characters to prevent selection jumps. Initial tests suggest this approach maintains the selection\'s integrity by providing a continuous selection path, even when dragging over \"dead space\". I\'ll re-evaluate how I implemented `PDFReader.tsx`\'s logic for rect acquisition to ensure that the selection stays within the intended boundaries of the text layer.\n\n\n**Adjusting Selection Logic**\n\nI\'m now changing the CSS to prevent the \"Panic Jump\" issue where selections extend beyond the text layer. This jump occurs because the browser\'s selection engine struggles to find a nearby text node. My current plan is to enable `user-select: text` on the `textLayer` container. However, I need to ensure that the user does not select the gap if they click empty space. I will now examine the `index.css` file and modify the settings there. My goal is for the span\'s to be selectable, but without extending the selection to other parts of the document.\n\n\n**Refining Selection Containment**\n\nI\'ve decided that a transparent overlay *within* the `textLayer`, but *behind* the spans, with `user-select: none`, is not the solution. It hinders click events. I\'m now realizing the \"jump\" issue likely originates from the browser selecting a node that encompasses the entire page. My `handleSelection` function in `PDFReader.tsx` is reacting to this selection. I\'m pivoting to CSS padding on spans, aiming to bridge gaps without excessive overlap, based on user feedback.\n\n\n**Analyzing Span Padding**\n\nI\'m now focusing on the \"Jump to whole page\" problem. I think I\'ve figured out why. I\'ll make the `br` elements in the PDF.js text layer *visible*, which will provide a clear line break. The other issue might be the `selectionchange` event, which could be triggered repeatedly, which could be causing a race condition in the browser\'s native selection UI. I\'ll test to see if a more stable hit area on spans helps. Also, I\'ll use a `range.getClientRects()` filter to ensure page selections only. I\'ll restart the development server to ensure my recent adjustments are active.\n\n\n\n**Refining Selection Flow**\n\nI\'m now changing my focus to the arrangement of the text spans. I\'ve realized that the \'inline-block\' display might be detrimental in an absolute context. Therefore, I\'m now making them `display: block` with `position: absolute`, which, because of PDF.js, they already are. I will also restore the `br` tags to their place. I\'m hopeful that will make selections more predictable. I\'m also ensuring the `range.getClientRects()` method is used. Also, I realized that the `user-select: none` on the container might be the root cause of the \"Panic Jump\" issue. I will modify the CSS to address this.\n\n\n**Testing Selection Interactivity**\n\nI\'m now implementing a new CSS approach to manage selections. The goal is to allow selections to pass through the container but only *start* on the spans themselves. I\'m setting `pointer-events: none` on the container to prevent starting selections in gaps, but I\'m simultaneously setting `user-select: text` on the container to facilitate the selection\'s continuation. I am also setting `pointer-events: auto` on the spans to allow selections to *start* there. I\'m curious to see if selections will be preserved on the spans when dragging between them. I\'m testing the `pointer-events` interaction now.\n\n\n\n"
