  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Refining Selection Boundaries**\n\nI\'ve finalized the requested changes, primarily focusing on refinements. I\'ve specifically confined text selection to the `.textLayer` and its children using `user-select: none` on reader containers. Additionally, I\'ve optimized text span hit areas to prevent selection gaps and inadvertent losses. I\'ve also implemented diagnostic logging to monitor selection boundary crossovers, enhancing my debugging capabilities. Furthermore, I\'ve ensured all aspects function properly, and am satisfied with progress.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I\'ve implemented several robust fixes to resolve the mobile text selection overflow bug, ensuring that dragging selection handles no longer triggers a fallback to selecting the entire page.\n\n### Key Changes:\n1.  **Selection Confinement**: Added `user-select: none` to all parent containers within the PDF reader (`.pdf-reader-root`, `.reader-sheet`, `.transform-container`, etc.). This prevents the browser from finding any selectable content outside of the intended text layers, effectively stopping the \"select all\" overflow logic.\n2.  **Hit Area Strengthening**: Optimized the `.textLayer span` elements by:\n    *   Switching to `display: inline-block` to better capture touch events.\n    *   Increasing the vertical footprint with `min-height: 1.1em` and `padding` to eliminate tiny gaps between lines.\n    *   Setting `box-sizing: content-box` to expand the hit area without interfering with the absolute positioning required by PDF.js.\n3.  **Diagnostic Logging**: Added a listener that monitors `mousemove` and `touchmove` while a selection is active. It logs a warning to the console if the user\'s focus leaves the `.textLayer` boundary, identifying the specific DOM node that intercepted the event.\n4.  **Touch Integrity**: Verified that all decorative overlays (gradients, shadows, spread seams) are set to `pointer-events: none`, ensuring they don\'t block the selection handles during precise adjustments.\n\nThese updates specifically target the \"jumpy\" behavior seen near line edges and in RTL (Arabic) text by ensuring the browser always has a valid, overlapping target to lock onto during a drag gesture.\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      nanos: 917623497
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
