  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Mobile Text Selection**\n\nI\'m focusing now on the persistent problems of text selection accuracy on mobile devices compared to PCs. It seems that there are continuing issues with jumping selections or selecting undesired text. This has been a recurring issue and bears further investigation.\n\n\n**Investigating Mobile Selection Interference**\n\nI\'ve been examining the interference of `user-select: none` on parent elements within PDF.js-like layers. It appears this can hinder the browser\'s ability to track selection handles across the container, especially if the handles are considered \"children\". This could explain why selections jump to entire lines or the whole page, as the browser might perceive the selection range as extending to the parent container.\n\n\n**Refining Touch Interaction Specifics**\n\nI\'m now focusing on mobile-specific issues, particularly the role of the magnifier and selection handles. It seems I should revisit the `pointer-events` settings, especially the interaction between the `.textLayer` and individual `span` elements. My goal is to balance precise character selection with accommodating touch interactions on mobile, and the `span` sizes and spacing might hold the key. I need to make sure I am not over-correcting for the PC version of this functionality.\n\n\n**Addressing Selection Anomalies**\n\nI\'m now focusing on specific mobile issues like selection cancellation and range expansion when the browser loses a text node under the touch. I\'m checking for overlays and `br` element interference, including `SelectionOverlay` and `SelectionMenu`. Further, I\'m examining how `user-select: none` on parent elements affects selection behavior, and whether a parent\'s unselectable state can interrupt the selection on children. I\'m exploring solutions like ensuring the immediate parent of text handles is selectable. I believe the proper handling of these immediate parents might be critical.\n\n\n**Optimizing Mobile Interaction**\n\nI\'m now investigating a fresh approach for mobile selection. I\'m focusing on expanding the touch hit area using padding on text spans without altering visual rectangles, as well as `-webkit-touch-callout: none` to block context menus. I\'m also examining the handling of text direction (specifically Arabic text) within spans and the `textLayer` div in `PDFReader.tsx`, since I have identified this as a key issue in the past. It appears that `pointer-events: none` on the container may be problematic.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 9
