  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Text Layer Styling**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the CSS applied to `textLayer span` elements. Key properties include `pointer-events: auto !important`, `display: inline-block`, `line-height: 1`, and the use of `min-height`, along with padding and margin values. These are critical for understanding how text selection and interaction are currently handled.\n\n\n**Investigating Mobile Selection Issues**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the mobile selection glitches. It seems the core problem lies in the conflicting `user-select` properties. Disabling selection on the parent elements (`reader-sheet`, `page-view-container`, etc.) to prevent unwanted parent selection, coupled with `user-select: text` on the `textLayer` introduces a mobile-specific edge case where handle dragging is inconsistent. The browser may lose focus of the selection or the handles disappear when they cross boundaries within the PDF. I will look further for a solution in the CSS.\n\n\n**Refining Touch Event Handling**\n\nI\'m now grappling with the `pointer-events` of the `textLayer`. When it is `none`, touch events pass to the parent, leading to mobile selection issues because of the `user-select: none` on the parents. Making the `textLayer` `pointer-events: auto` to fix this would disable background page interaction. The current thought is to only make the `textLayer` `pointer-events: auto` when a selection is active to allow touch event capture only when needed, but the plan has evolved to an alternate solution. I can fix \"select all\" triggers.\n\n\n**Optimizing Span Selection Stickiness**\n\nI\'m now focusing on improving selection handle \"stickiness\" on mobile. The recent approach involved reintroducing pseudo-elements on spans to create horizontal bridges, which didn\'t pan out. I removed them previously. Now, I will ensure that the `textLayer` spans effectively \"touch\" each other to increase the hit area for selection. I am exploring whether `-webkit-user-select: text` on the `.textLayer` container is sufficient, even with parent elements set to `user-select: none`. I\'m also addressing the issue where a long press can cause the browser to attempt to select the entire `div.textLayer`.\n\n\n**Addressing Mobile Selection Jumps**\n\nI\'ve been examining the `pointer-events` on `.textLayer` again, and realized it\'s a key factor in mobile \"empty space\" touch issues. When `pointer-events: none`, long presses are passed to underlying elements (e.g., canvas, `page-view-container`), which have `user-select: none`. This leads to the undesirable behavior of whole-page selection. I think the viewport container\'s strictness is key to fixing this and preventing jumping selections. The spans will be adjusted.\n\n\n**Refining RTL Selection**\n\nI\'m now focusing on Arabic text selection issues, where the browser incorrectly selects lines in the opposite direction. The issue seems related to how PDF.js generates spans for RTL text, which confuses the browser\'s selection logic. I\'m experimenting with increasing the vertical hit area of `textLayer` spans to bridge lines and prevent accidental \"upward\" selections. I\'m also planning to set `user-select: none` on the `selection-overlay-layer` to refine the selection behavior and remove any unneeded elements.\n\n\n**Improving Selection Stability**\n\nI\'m now investigating selection jump issues. My diagnostic logging confirms the problem: selection is lost when the pointer leaves the `.textLayer`. The user\'s description, \"jumps to select the whole page,\" provides valuable insight. I\'m considering `touch-action: pan-x pan-y` (or `touch-action: none` during selection) on the container to prevent this. I am trying to fix the issues, not prevent selection altogether. I am planning to remove the `selectionchange` trigger.\n\n\n\n**Evaluating Transform Impacts**\n\nMy current focus is on the `transform` property. Zooming and panning with `scale` and `panX/Y` can cause selection issues. Selection rects and handles inside the scaled container drift or trigger OS bugs. I\'m considering these transform-related challenges with the goal of more stable selection.\n\n\n**Adjusting Spacing and Selection**\n\nI\'m now focusing on fixing horizontal gaps in spans to improve mobile selection. My thought is that adjusting `letter-spacing` might help bridge the characters, and I will be looking closely at `line-height` and vertical spacing between lines. This may provide a clue to solve the problem where the browser appears to select whole pages.\n\n\n**Refining Selection Bridges**\n\nI\'m now focusing on mobile text selection by making the spans slightly larger with `min-height: 1.3em` and `margin: -0.1em 0`, and I am hoping this will improve the hit area. I have tried and discarded many variations, including an invisible selection bridge. I will also make `pointer-events: auto` on `textLayer` during selection using `isSelectionActiveRef`. I will try `-webkit-user-drag: none`.\n\n\n\n**Isolating Mobile Selection**\n\nI\'m now focusing on mobile selection isolation to avoid \"container selection\". My idea is to make sure the handles remain within a defined area. I\'m trying several changes including making spans touch each other and adding `pointer-events: none` to the `.textLayer`. I will use `display: block` and a slightly increased `min-height` for span elements. I will not use `scale` to prevent coordinate drift. I now remember that spans are usually absolutely positioned.\n\n\n**Refining Handle Anchors**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the selection handle behavior, and it appears the `display` property, although not crucial for layout, significantly impacts handle anchor placement. I\'m also now adjusting `index.css` to bridge horizontal gaps between spans. Padding and margin tweaks are the first change.\n\n\n**Prioritizing Event Handling**\n\nI\'m now focusing on how touch events interact with selection. I\'m exploring setting `pointer-events: auto` on `.textLayer` but with `touch-action: pan-x pan-y` to allow native selection and browser panning. However, I must be careful with Framer Motion\'s `onPan` and ensure it doesn\'t interfere with native selection, but handles panning. My `handlePointerDown` function will be updated.\n\n\n**Managing Touch Interaction**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential conflicts between native browser selection and Framer Motion\'s event handling. I\'m noting that while `handlePanMove` now correctly returns during `SelectingText` mode, `onPan` might still be capturing events, causing conflicts. The OS handles selection handle dragging, so my goal is to ensure smooth transitions between selection and panning. I will be sure to disable `onPan` on handle selection.\n\n\n**Refining Text Selection Control**\n\nI\'m now prioritizing the accuracy of `SelectingText` mode. To prevent page jumps, I will now check `window.getSelection().toString()` before triggering any custom gestures. This should help me better detect when a user is interacting with an OS selection handle, making my changes more robust.\n\n\n**Testing Pointer Events**\n\nI\'m now focusing on a significant hypothesis regarding `pointer-events: none` on the `.textLayer` div. My line of reasoning is that while this setting prevents selection *between* spans, it might be the root cause of the invalid selections. If the browser sees the parent as `user-select: none`, and the `.textLayer` spans, which are touchable, it might flag these as invalid selections because of the touch \"gaps\" between spans. If true, this could be key.\n\n\n**Enhancing Span Overlap**\n\nI\'m now implementing significantly increased padding and negative margin on the spans to create substantial overlap, increasing the hit area for mobile selection. I will now adjust the `SelectingText` detection for increased robustness. I\'ll test it out and move forward.\n\n\n**Refining Selection Guards**\n\nI\'m now implementing more robust selection guards within `PDFReader.tsx`. Specifically, I am adding a check in `handlePanMove` to stop panning when a selection is active, leveraging `window.getSelection()?.type === \'Range\'` to prevent unintended page movement during text selection. I\'m also looking at `br` element styling to ensure they occupy sufficient vertical space, because of the inline display.\n\n\n**Verifying Overlay Depth**\n\nI\'m now investigating potential layering issues. I\'ve confirmed that the `textLayer`\'s `z-index` (60) is correctly positioned above the `SelectionOverlay` (55), and the `pointer-events: none` on overlay elements is also as expected. However, the use of `user-select: none` on the `selection-overlay-layer` remains a detail of concern.\n\n\n**Refining Page Edge Interactions**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the \"select all\" triggers that happen when selection handles go to the edge of the page. The user\'s description is very clear. My hypothesis is that the selection handles are escaping the spans and triggering the \"Select All\" browser behavior. I\'m going to carefully review the `pointer-events` on the `.textLayer` container again, since that\'s critical in determining where touch events are sent.\n\n\n**Addressing Touch Target Detection**\n\nI\'m now investigating touch target detection. My goal is to prevent unintended selections when dragging handles. The \"gap\" between spans, with `pointer-events: none`, redirects touch events, which can be the root cause of the \"select all\" triggers on page edges. The strategy now is to use `pointer-events: auto` on `.textLayer`, and ensure `onPointerDown` handles events only on spans and `touch-action: pan-x pan-y`. I\'m going to test my assumption on touch landing.\n\n\n**Confirming Event Ownership**\n\nI\'ve confirmed that my code, specifically the `onPan` handler, is intercepting touch events intended for the browser\'s selection engine when those events land outside of the selectable spans, such as in the background, where a touch target does not exist. This is the \"Select All\" issue. To fix this, I will set `pointer-events: auto` on `.textLayer`, then use `touch-action: pan-x pan-y` on `.textLayer` to ensure the events are owned correctly by the intended targets. The goal is that touch events in the background will bubble up. I will check click event bubbling.\n\n\n**Refining Touch Event Routing**\n\nI\'m now focused on the conflict between text selection and panning. I\'m aiming to bridge all gaps in the `textLayer` spans with padding and touch overlap. The plan involves disabling gestures if any text is selected, specifically by checking `window.getSelection()?.type === \'Range\'` in `handlePanMove`. I am refining my logic and checking `isSelectionActiveRef.current`.\n\n\n**Debugging Selection Jump Behavior**\n\nI\'m now investigating a potential reset issue with `isSelectionActiveRef.current`. My current hypothesis is that the 100ms timeout I implemented might be interfering with touch handle selection. The existing code checks for selection active, but there\'s a chance the browser resets selection rapidly. The goal is to make the spans solid horizontal blocks, and use `display: flex`.\n\n\n\n**Improving Handle Stability**\n\nI\'m now focusing on mobile handle behavior and selection direction. I\'ve realized `direction: rtl` must be applied to spans correctly to handle Arabic text, but will test on LTR spans too. I will check `ltr` and `rtl` class application, to ensure the OS and spans are in alignment. I\'m prioritizing adding a \"massive hit area\" to spans. I\'ll be checking `window.getSelection().type === \'Range\'` to check selection.\n\n\n"
