  planner_response {
    modified_response: "I have implemented synthetic line wrappers by creating full-width transparent hit-regions that cover each line of text.\n\n### Implementation Details:\n1.  **Synthetic Hit-Zones**: In `PDFReader.tsx`, after `pdfjs.renderTextLayer` runs, I now automatically calculate the line boundary for each row of text (top position and height) and append a full-width `div` with `user-select: text` to act as a hit-region.\n    *   This ensures that even if your finger drags through empty whitespace after a word or between fragmented spans, the selection engine remains anchored to the same logical line.\n2.  **CSS Hardening**: Updated `index.css` to add the `.text-line-hitbox` class with `pointer-events: auto` and `z-index: 55`, ensuring it intercepts selection focus without obstructing the visual text spans.\n3.  **Canvas Isolation**: Explicitly locked all canvas-based decorative layers to `pointer-events: none !important` to prevent them from stealing touch events during selection.\n\nThis approach creates the \"continuous hit-region\" effect similar to native text selection in apps like Apple Books. Please let me know how it performs now in your mobile browser."
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
