  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Mobile Selection Issues**\n\nI\'m currently focused on the frustrating text selection problems reported within the mobile PDF reader app, particularly on iOS/Safari. Moving selection handles into whitespace at line ends triggers unpredictable behavior: jumps, reversals, and incorrect region selections. I\'m prioritizing understanding how these interactions are failing.\n\n\n**Refining Continuous Line Selection**\n\nI\'ve been trying to solve continuous line selection and have moved away from synthetic hitboxes. They interfered with selection ownership, so I\'m now exploring approaches that avoid introducing artificial DOM elements. I\'m focusing on \"continuous line selection hit-testing\" directly. My recent attempts with CSS `pointer-events` tweaks and disabling CSS have yielded inconsistent results, highlighting the complexity of ensuring seamless, natural selection behavior within the `textLayer`.\n\n\n**Expanding Text Spans**\n\nI\'m now thinking the issue of line selection on mobile may be the huge gaps in `pdf.js` output text spans, causing the selection range anchor to be lost and reset. I\'m exploring expanding existing span elements so they slightly overlap, bridging gaps without affecting visual layout or ownership. Dragging through whitespace must remain attached to the same text row. I\'m taking a close look at the current CSS for `.textLayer span` now.\n\n\n**Investigating DOM Interference**\n\nI\'m now reconsidering the current DOM manipulation, particularly the padding and margin tweaks on text spans. It seems they might be contributing to the selection issues. I\'m focusing on whether we can avoid any DOM modifications entirely, and instead ensure the `textLayer` container doesn\'t interfere. I also suspect the JavaScript logic within `PDFReader.tsx`, specifically the `handleSelection` function and its reliance on `range.getClientRects()`, might be the culprit. I am analyzing the implications of `rawRects` used in `handleSelection` to see if they might be a cause.\n\n\n"
    thinking_duration {
      seconds: 3
      nanos: 424920040
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
