  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Analyzing Selection Activation**\n\nI\'ve been examining the `handleSelection` function within the `PDFPage` component. My focus is on how it manages selection rects. Specifically, I noted the clearing behavior: it happens if the selection is inactive or if it\'s external to the page layer. The function checks `isActive` via the presence of a selection and its `type` property.\n\n\n**Refining Selection Handling**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the \"jump/glitch\" issue with selection. The bottleneck lies in how the `handleSelection` function reacts when the native selection range becomes temporarily invalid or collapses. It seems that when the selection handle enters empty space and `isActive` becomes false, the UI disappears prematurely. To fix this, I propose we hold onto the previous `selectionRects` for a short time, assuming the user is still interacting. Also, I\'ve realized `handleSelection` isn\'t receiving the pointer event, but `isSelectionActiveRef` *is* tracking selection.\n\n\n**Revising Span Behavior**\n\nI\'ve just realized a key point: the `selectionchange` event directly reflects the browser\'s updated selection state. This means `handleSelection` is merely reacting to the browser\'s behavior. Preventing the browser from \"hijacking\" the selection is tricky. My new strategy centers on expanding the text spans to cover entire lines, which will ensure that the browser always identifies a text span, even in whitespace. I\'m exploring how to safely achieve this without disrupting the current layout. Currently, the spans are `inline-block`, with padding and line-height. I\'m hesitant to make them `block` and `width:100%`, as this could break the layout.\n\n\n"
