  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Refining Selectability Control**\n\nI\'ve made progress by isolating selection ownership to `spans` via `user-select: none` on `.textLayer`. To improve Safari behavior, I simplified the display to `inline` for `spans`. This change specifically tackles Safari\'s re-anchoring issue by shifting ownership.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I have investigated the selection overflow issue on iOS Safari. The primary cause was the browser\'s native selection engine re-anchoring to parent containers when drag gestures entered whitespace between fragmented text spans.\n\nI have applied the following fixes:\n\n1.  **Selection Ownership Isolation**:\n    *   Set `.textLayer` to `user-select: none !important`. This forces the browser to ignore the container entirely and only anchor selection to the internal text `span`s.\n    *   Confirmed `.pdf-reader-root` and other UI containers are set to `user-select: none` to prevent whole-page selection.\n\n2.  **Text Span Geometry Stability**:\n    *   Changed `display: inline-block` to `display: inline` for all `.textLayer span` elements. This is more robust in Safari forMaintaining selection range continuity across word boundaries, as it avoids some of the block-level rendering quirks that can trigger re-anchoring.\n\nThese changes limit the browser\'s selection targets strictly to the text spans, which should significantly improve the stability of selection dragging through whitespace."
    thinking_duration {
      nanos: 202010314
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
