  planner_response {
    thinking: "**Addressing the Frustration**\n\nI\'m now zeroing in on the user\'s frustration with unstable text selection in their PDF viewer. The core issue appears when dragging across whitespace. I\'m focusing on the nature of this \"instability\". Is it a rendering glitch, a misinterpretation of the input, or something else entirely? The next step will be breaking down the technical requirements implied by this complaint.\n\n\n"
    modified_response: "I understand precisely why your selection is breaking.\n\n### Here is the problem:\n\nPDF readers rendered with `pdf.js` do not actually exist as a \"document\" in your browser. They are a collection of individual text `<span>` elements positioned absolutely on top of the PDF image.\n\nWhen you drag your finger to select text, you are jumping between these tiny, disconnected boxes.\n1.  **The Breakdown:** As soon as your finger moves into the tiny gap of \"empty space\" between words or at the end of a line, the browser\'s native selection engine loses the \"text\" context.\n2.  **The Hijack:** The browser realizes it is no longer touching a selectable text span, so it tries to \"help\" by re-anchoring *somewhere else* in the DOM\342\200\224often grabbing the nearest parent container or the entire page, which is why your selection suddenly jumps or expands to cover huge areas.\n\n### The Fix:\nWe need to make these disconnected boxes behave as if they are a continuous line to the browser\'s touch engine, **without** adding fake overlays (which just cause more interference).\n\nMy approach to fix this is:\n1.  **Strict Selection Ownership:** Ensure only the `<span>` elements themselves are selectable (`user-select: text`) and everything else is locked down (`user-select: none`).\n2.  **Hit-area Repair:** Instead of overlays, I will use CSS to make the `<span>` elements themselves have \"invisible\" margins that bridge the tiny gaps between words. This keeps the browser\'s \"selection context\" active even when your finger is in the micro-gap between words.\n3.  **Safari Stability:** Remove all `pointer-events: none` hacks that cause the browser to switch selection modes on iOS.\n\n**Should I proceed with applying this precise minimal-CSS fix to bridge the spans, while rolling back the recent overlay-based experiments that caused these glitches?**"
    thinking_duration {
      nanos: 964553015
    }
    stop_reason: STOP_REASON_STOP_PATTERN
  }
}
steps {
  type: CORTEX_STEP_TYPE_USER_INPUT
